WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:03.919
and takes a model that has been trained on protein data.

00:04.360 --> 00:09.270
So if you look at this protein, it is simply a sequence of amino acids.

00:09.290 --> 00:11.314
And these amino acids, they all have names.

00:11.494 --> 00:13.358
I think I have a table somewhere here.

00:14.741 --> 00:14.921
Yes.

00:15.242 --> 00:18.428
So these are the different amino acids that exist.

00:18.408 --> 00:25.279
And you can see a protein is simply a sequence of these names.

00:25.479 --> 00:31.629
So usually they're abbreviated by like a three-letter abbreviation or just a one-letter abbreviation.

00:31.949 --> 00:40.483
So a protein might be A, V, M, M, V, A, G and so on.

00:40.463 --> 00:42.867
And this is just a string of text, right?

00:43.167 --> 00:46.853
So what I can do is I can train a language model on this.

00:46.953 --> 00:54.545
A language model is simply a model that takes a piece of text and tells you what's the next piece of text.

00:54.726 --> 00:55.747
So what's the next letter?

00:55.807 --> 00:56.709
What's the next word?

00:56.929 --> 00:59.333
In this case, what's the next amino acid?

00:59.313 --> 01:03.060
And we can use tools from NLP for that.

01:03.080 --> 01:06.006
Specifically, we can train a BERT model.

01:06.066 --> 01:10.294
A BERT works a bit differently than a standard language model.

01:10.354 --> 01:12.959
BERT does what is called masked language modeling.

01:13.300 --> 01:17.709
So you would take this string, you would feed it into a BERT model right here.

01:17.769 --> 01:22.097
And I've made an entire video on BERT if you want to check that out.

01:22.077 --> 01:27.243
And what you'll do by inputting that, you'll mask out some of the tokens.

01:27.483 --> 01:33.049
So you'll maybe mask out this one, mask out this one, and then you ask the model to reconstruct those.

01:33.590 --> 01:37.194
We say that here is an M and here is an A without seeing them.

01:37.474 --> 01:46.064
So the model somehow has to learn from the surrounding amino acids what this amino acid could be.

01:47.205 --> 01:49.468
So it has to reconstruct this sequence.

01:49.448 --> 01:58.059
So, the hope here is in natural language is that Burt somehow learns something about language itself.

01:58.499 --> 02:06.049
By being able to reconstruct these things, it has learned something about language, about which words appear together and when.

02:06.509 --> 02:13.498
It might even learn very long distance relationships between words just because it has to predict those.

02:14.812 --> 02:17.556
the idea carries over to biology.

02:17.997 --> 02:31.879
So we might hope that a BERT trained on an amino acid sequence will learn something about the language of proteins about the amino acid sequence.

02:32.220 --> 02:35.385
And our goal here is to be to ask

02:35.365 --> 02:44.473
Can we somehow infer the 3D shape of a protein, which is the important part, from its sequence right here?

02:44.593 --> 02:49.157
So given its sequence, can we infer the 3D shape?

02:49.698 --> 02:54.222
Now, as I understand it, usually this has to be done in like a simulation.

02:54.302 --> 03:05.372
So you would build this in a simulator and then you do like some sort of a molecule simulation to see how this ends up in a 3D shape.

03:05.352 --> 03:22.528
you could train a model to just predict the 3D shape but in this case we're just interested what does the BERT model learn about the 3D shape while only ever having been trained on predicting the next or predicting the sequence of amino acids.

03:22.548 --> 03:27.297
So it's never been trained to to look at the 3D shape and that's our goal here.

